f Florida's Missions for Carolina Indian Relations and the Origins of the Yamasee War / rDixon, Bradley -- tPART IV. TRADE AND WAR -- tChapter 10. Reluctant Petitioners: English Officials and the Spanish Caribbean / rHatfield, April Lee -- tChapter 11. Enabling, Implementing, Experiencing Entanglement: Empires, Sailors, and Coastal Peoples in the British-Spanish Caribbean / rBassi, Ernesto -- tChapter 12. The Seven Years' War and the Globalization of Anglo-Iberian Imperial Entanglement: The View from Manila / rFlannery, Kristie Patricia -- tAfterword / rGould, Eliga H. -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments  aAccording to conventional wisdom, in the sixteenth century, Spain and Portugal served as a model to the English for how to go about establishing colonies in the New World and Africa. By the eighteenth century, however, it was Spain and Portugal that aspired to imitate the British. Editor Jorge Cañizares-Esguerra and the contributors to Entangled Empires challenge these long-standing assumptions, exploring how Spain, Britain, and Portugal shaped one another throughout the entire period, from the sixteenth to the nineteenth centuries. They argue that these empires were interconnected from the very outset in their production and sharing of knowledge as well as in their economic activities. Willingly or unwillingly, African slaves, Amerindians, converso traders, smugglers, missionaries, diplomats, settlers, soldiers, and pirates crossed geographical, linguistic, and political boundaries and cocreated not only local but also imperial histories. Contributors reveal that entanglement was not merely a process that influenced events in the colonies after their founding; it was constitutive of European empire from the beginning.The essays in Entangled Empires seek to clarify the processes that rendered the intertwined histories of these colonial worlds invisible, including practices of archival erasure as well as selective memorialization. Bringing together a large geography and chronology, Entangled Empires emphasizes the importance of understanding connections, both intellectual and practical, between the English and Iberian imperial projects. The colonial history of the United States ought to be considered part of the history of colonial Latino-America just as Latin-American history should be understood as fundamental to the formation of the United States.Contributors: Ernesto Bassi, Benjamin Breen, Jorge Cañizares-Esguerra, Bradley Dixon, Kristie Flannery, Eliga Gould, Michael Guasco, April Hatfield, Christopher Heaney, Christopher Schmidt-Nowara, Mark Sheaves, Holly Snyder, Cameron Strang.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Sep 2018) 0aCivilization, Modern. 0aHistory, Modern. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aAfrican-American Studies. 4aAmerican History. 4aAmerican Studies. 4aEuropean History. 4aWorld History.1 aCañizares-Esguerra, Jorge, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishz978311060403008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2018z9783110603149oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook package 2017-2019z978311065989408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2017-2018z978311065747008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniv.of Pennsylvania Press eBook-Package 2018z978311060663840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812294699423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812294699.jpg  a978-3-11-060403-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2018 Englishb2018  a978-3-11-060